Pharmacokinetics of the selective prostacyclin receptor agonist

Abstract
1. This study examined the pharmacokinetics, distribution, metabolism and excretion of the
selective prostacyclin receptor agonist selexipag (NS-304; ACT-293987) and its active
metabolite MRE-269 (ACT-33679). The compounds were investigated following oral and/or
intravenous administration to intact rats, dogs and monkeys, and bile-duct-cannulated rats
and dogs.
2. After oral administration of [
14
C]selexipag, selexipag was well absorbed in rats and dogs with
total recoveries of over 90% of the dose, mainly in the faeces. Biliary excretion was the major
elimination pathway for [
14
C]MRE-269 as well as [
14
C]selexipag, while renal elimination was
of little importance. [
14
C]Selexipag-related radioactivity was secreted into the milk in
lactating rats.
3. Plasma was analysed for total radioactivity, selexipag and MRE-269 in rats and monkeys.
Selexipag was negligible in rat plasma due to extensive metabolism, and MRE-269 was
present in rat and monkey plasma. A species difference was clearly evident when selexipag
was incubated in rat, dog and monkey plasma.
4. Total radioactivity was rapidly distributed to tissues. The highest concentrations were found
in the bile duct and liver without significant accumulation or persistence, while there was
limited melanin-associated binding, penetration of the blood–brain barrier and placental
transfer of drug-related materials.
Keywords
Distribution, excretion, hydrolysis, mass
balance, prostacyclin receptor agonist,
pharmacokinetics, selexipag

Introduction
Selexipag (2-{4-[(5,6-diphenylpyrazin-2-yl)(isopropyl)amino]
butoxy}-N-(methylsulfonyl)acetamide) is a potent, orally
active, selective prostacyclin (PGI
2
) receptor agonist which
is rapidly hydrolysed to the active metabolite MRE-269 ({4-
[(5,6-diphenylpyrazin-2-yl)(propan-2-yl)amino]butoxy}acetic
acid) (Asaki et al., 2015; Kuwano et al., 2007). The chemical
structures of selexipag and MRE-269, which are different
from PGI
2
analogues, are shown in Figure 1.
In the clinic, selexipag demonstrated a significant improve-
ment in disease progression in patients with pulmonary
arterial hypertension (PAH) (Scott, 2016). The US Food and
Drug Administration approved selexipag for the treatment of
PAH in 2015, while the European Medicines Agency and the
Japanese Pharmaceuticals and Medical Devices Agency
approved selexipag for the treatment of PAH in 2016.
The purpose of the present study was to investigate the
pharmacokinetics, distribution, metabolism and excretion of
selexipag in rats, dogs and monkeys after a single dose of
[
14
C]selexipag. In addition, the pharmacokinetics of the active
metabolite [
14
C]MRE-269 were investigated.
Materials and methods
Chemicals and reagents
[
14
C]Selexipag and its metabolite [
14
C]MRE-269 (Figure 1)
were synthesised from [ring-U-
14
C]benzil at Nippon
Shinyaku. The specific activity of [
14
C]selexipag was 4.15
MBq (112 mCi) per mg and that of [
14
C]MRE-269 was 5.00
MBq (135 mCi) per mg. The radiochemical purity of both
compounds was 98%. Selexipag and MRE-269 standards were
synthesised at Nippon Shinyaku. General purpose reagents
and solvents were of analytical grade (or a suitable alterna-
tive) and were obtained principally from Nacalai Tesque
(Kyoto, Japan) and Wako Chemicals (Osaka, Japan). The
liquid scintillation cocktails used were Emulsifier Scintillator
Plus, Hionic-Fluor, Aquasafe 500 Plus and Permafluor E
+
(PerkinElmer, Waltham, MA). Test compounds were prepared
as suspensions in 0.5% (w/v) aqueous methylcellulose for oral

containing 0.01% (w/v) sodium carbonate for intravenous
administration. Pooled plasma fractions treated with heparin

Pharmaceuticals (Allschwil, Switzerland), Charles River

Treatment and Management of Animals (Law No. 105, 1

Pharmacokinetics in plasma and mass balance
Rat studies
Male Sprague–Dawley rats weighing approximately 230 g
were obtained from Japan SLC (Shizuoka, Japan). A single
oral dose of [
14
C]selexipag was given to 15 male rats by
gastric gavage at a dose level of 1 mg/kg (112 mCi/kg). A
single bolus intravenous dose of [
14
C]MRE-269 was given to
15 male rats at a dose level of 0.845 mg/kg (56 mCi/kg) via the
jugular vein. Blood samples of approximately 1.5 mL were
taken from the jugular vein or whole blood samples were
taken from the abdominal aorta under isoflurane anaesthesia
0.25, 0.5, 1, 2, 4, 6, 8, 24 and 48 h after oral administration
and 0.083, 0.25, 0.5, 1, 2, 4, 6, 8, 24 and 48 h after intravenous
administration. The blood was collected into heparinised test
tubes, and plasma was prepared by centrifugation. Three male
Sprague–Dawley rats were used for the mass balance study
and each received a single oral dose of [
14
C]selexipag at 1 mg/
kg (28 mCi/kg) or a single intravenous dose of [
14
C]MRE-269
at 0.845 mg/kg (17 mCi/kg). Urine and faecal samples from
the three animals were collected into containers at 24-h
intervals after oral or intravenous administration until 168 h
post-dose. Expired air was collected for 24 h after intravenous
administration for assessment of
14
CO
2
expiration. The cages
were washed with suitable amounts of water 168 h post-dose,
and the washings were retained with the excreta.
Dog studies
Three male beagle dogs weighing 7–9 kg were obtained
from Marshall Farms (North Rose, NY). An oral dose
of [
14
C]selexipag was given at a dose level of 2 mg/kg
(18 mCi/kg) by gastric gavage. Following a wash-out period of
five weeks between administrations, a single bolus intraven-
ous dose of [
14
C]selexipag was given at a dose level of
1 mg/kg (14 mCi/kg) via the cephalic vein. Urine was quan-
titatively collected into containers cooled by solid CO
2
for the
periods 0–6 and 6–24 h, and then at 24-h intervals up to 192 h
post-dose. Faeces were quantitatively collected at 24-h
intervals up to 192 h post-dose. At the time of each daily
collection, the cages were washed with water and the
washings retained.
Monkey studies
Three male cynomolgus monkeys weighing 3–4 kg were
obtained from Siconbrec (Rizal, Philippines). An oral dose of
[
14
C]selexipag was given at a dose level of 0.25 mg/kg (28
mCi/kg) by gastric gavage. Following a wash-out period of
three weeks between administrations, a single bolus intraven-
ous dose of [
14
C]selexipag or [
14
C]MRE-269 was given at a
dose level of 0.25 mg/kg (20 mCi/kg) or 0.211 mg/kg (21 mCi/
kg) via the saphenous vein. Blood samples of approximately
1.5 mL were taken from the saphenous vein 0.25, 0.5, 1, 2, 4,
6, 8, 24, 48, 72 and 168 h after oral administration and 0.083,
0.25, 0.5, 1, 2, 4, 6, 8, 24, 48, 72 and 168 h after intravenous
administration. The blood was collected into heparinised test
tubes, and plasma was prepared by centrifugation. Urine and
faecal samples from the three animals were quantitatively
collected into containers at 24-h intervals after oral or
intravenous administration until 168 h post-dose. The cages
were washed daily with suitable amounts of water, and the
washings were retained with the excreta.
Biliary excretion studies
Biliary excretion was studied in two male Sprague–Dawley
rats (body weight, approximately 250 g; RCC, Fu
¨
llinsdorf,
Switzerland) and two male beagle dogs (body weight,
approximately 13.5 kg) using bile-duct cannulation. Prior to
dosing, the animals underwent bile-duct-cannulation surgery
as described by Treiber et al. (2016). [
14
C]Selexipag was
administered orally and intravenously to rats at total doses of
20 and 0.9 mg/kg, respectively, each containing radioactive
target doses of 100 mCi/kg. Bile, urine and faeces were
collected at predefined intervals over periods of 80 and 96 h
for intravenous and oral administration, respectively. Bile-
duct-cannulated dogs received oral and intravenous
[
14
C]selexipag at doses of 2 and 1 mg/kg, respectively, and
intravenous [
14
C]MRE-269 at a dose of 1 mg/kg. The
radioactive doses of both compounds were 200 mCi/animal.
Urine and bile were quantitatively collected into containers
cooled by solid CO
2
for the periods 0–6 and 6–24 h, and then
at 24-h intervals up to 96 h post-dose. Faeces were

14

quantitatively collected at 24-h intervals up to 96 h post-dose.
At the time of each daily collection all debris (waste food) was
separately removed, and the cages were washed with water.
The debris and cage washings were retained.
Enterohepatic recirculation study
The potential for enterohepatic recirculation of MRE-269 was
investigated after intravenous administration of [
14
C]MRE-
269 to bile-duct-cannulated Sprague–Dawley rats (body
weight, approximately 230 g; Japan SLC) at a dose of
0.845 mg/kg (17 mCi/kg). Bile was collected individually
from three dosed (donor) animals for 3 h, pooled, and re-
infused into the duodenum of three bile-duct-cannulated
(receiver) animals. Urine, bile and faeces were quantitatively
collected from the receiver animals over a period of 24 h to
estimate the extent of enterohepatic recirculation.
Milk excretion study
Three female Sprague–Dawley rats (body weight, approxi-
mately 260 g; Charles River Laboratories, Kanagawa, Japan)
were used for this study and each received a single oral dose
of [
14
C]selexipag at 1 mg/kg (55 mCi/kg). Milk and blood
were collected at 0.5, 1, 2, 4, 8, 24, 48 and 72 h post-dose. The
rats were given an intraperitoneal injection of oxytocin (0.5 U
per animal) 30 min before milk collection to stimulate
lactation. The rats were anaesthetised before the start of
milk collection, and approximately 0.1 mL of milk was
collected from each rat using a pipette. The weight of each
milk sample was recorded. Blood samples of approximately
0.25 mL were taken from the caudal vein. The blood was
collected into heparinised test tubes, and plasma was prepared
by centrifugation.
Radioactivity analysis
For the determination of radioactivity in rat excreta, urine
samples (10–15 mL) were diluted with water to a final volume
of 50 mL, and faecal samples (6–8 g) were homogenised in
water to a final weight of 60–70 g. For the determination of
radioactivity in dog excreta, urine samples (0.1–1 mL) were
diluted with water to a final volume of 1 mL, and faecal
samples were homogenised in water (approximately 1:1, w/v).
For the determination of radioactivity in monkey excreta,
urine samples (50–450 mL) were diluted with water to a final
volume of 150–600 mL, and faecal samples (30–150 g) were
homogenised in water to a final weight of 500–700 g.
Radioactivity in samples of plasma (0.05–0.5 mL), diluted
urine (0.5 mL) and bile (0.03 mL) was determined after the
addition of scintillation cocktail (10 mL; Emulsifier
Scintillator Plus or Aquasafe 500 Plus) in a liquid scintillation
counter (Tri-Carb 2300 TR or 3100 TR; PerkinElmer). For the
determination of radioactivity in samples of faecal homogen-
ate, weighed homogenate aliquots (0.5 g) were mixed with the
tissue solubiliser Solvable (PerkinElmer), 30% (w/v) hydro-
gen peroxide solution and Hionic-Fluor scintillation cocktail
(10 mL), and then counted in a liquid scintillation counter.
Radioactivity in samples of milk (0.1 mL) was determined
after the addition of the tissue solubiliser Soluene-350
(PerkinElmer) and Hionic-Fluor scintillation cocktail
(10 mL). In dog studies, weighed duplicate 0.3-g portions of
faecal homogenate were combusted in a PerkinElmer 307
sample oxidiser. The
14
CO
2
generated was collected by
adsorption on activated charcoal (8 mL; Carbosorb;
PerkinElmer) to which Permafluor E
+
scintillation cocktail
(10 mL) had been added. The amount of radioactivity in the
plasma was expressed as ng-equivalents of selexipag or MRE-
269/mL and was calculated by using the specific activity of
the dose administered. The amount of radioactivity in the
urine and faeces was expressed as a percentage of the total
amount of radioactivity administered to each animal. The
lower limit of quantification was considered to be twice the
background rate of 15–20 dpm.
Determination of selexipag and MRE-269
concentrations in plasma
To 0.5 mL of plasma in a 10-mL centrifuge tube, 0.5 mL of
purified water, 0.5 mL of 0.1 mol/L hydrochloric acid and
5 mL of ethyl acetate were added. The sample was mixed for
10 min and then centrifuged for 10 min at 2160 g. The
aqueous phase was discarded, and the organic phase was
evaporated to dryness. The residue was reconstituted in 50 mL
of methanol and 2–3 mL of the methanolic solution spotted on
precoated Silica Gel 60 F
254
plates (Merck). The plates were
developed to a distance of 150 mm with a mobile phase
consisting of a mixture of dichloromethane:methanol:formic
acid (10:2:0.1 v/v/v) and then dried. After exposure in a
copper-and-lead-lined exposure box (BAS-SHB 2040;
FujiFilm, Tokyo, Japan), the imaging plates (FujiFilm) were
scanned using a BAS-2500 radioluminography system
(FujiFilm) to determine the fraction percent of selexipag or
MRE-269 on the thin-layer chromatography (TLC) plates.
Plasma-concentration–time curves in rats were generated by
plotting the mean value at each collecting time post-dose.
Pharmacokinetic analysis
The pharmacokinetic parameters of the radioactivity, selex-
ipag and MRE-269 in plasma were calculated with Phoenix
WinNonlin Professional version 5.2.1 (Pharsight, Mountain
View, CA). The peak plasma concentration (C
max
) and the
time to the peak concentration (t
max
) were determined by
inspection of the raw data. The elimination rate constant (k
el
)
was estimated by linear regression of the terminal phase of the
log plasma-concentration–time curves, and the elimination
half-life (t
1/2
) was calculated as ln2/k
el
. The area under the
plasma-concentration–time curve (AUC
0–1
) was calculated
by the trapezoidal rule with extrapolation to infinity.
Quantitative whole-body autoradiography
Albino Sprague–Dawley rats (18 males, six nulliparous
females and four pregnant females calculated to be at day
17 of gestation at dosing) and six pigmented Lister hooded
rats (body weight, 194–318 g) were supplied by Harlan UK
(Bicester, Oxfordshire, UK). The dose was administered by
gastric gavage at a dose level of 0.9 mg/kg [
14
C]selexipag
(100 mCi/kg). Under deep isoflurane anaesthesia, rats were
killed by cold shock and frozen at 1, 8, 24, 72, 168 and 504 h
post-dose (the males, nulliparous females and pigmented rats)
DOI: 10.1080/00498254.2017.1294277 Pharmacokinetics of selexipag in animals 3
and 1, 8, 24 and 72 h post-dose (the pregnant rats). Blood was
collected by cardiac puncture from the anaesthetised animals
prior to freezing and was centrifuged to prepare plasma,
which was analysed by liquid scintillation counting. The legs,
tail and whiskers were trimmed off each animal and the
frozen carcass was set in a block of aqueous 2% (w/v)
carboxymethylcellulose. The block was mounted onto the
stage of a Leica CM3600 cryomicrotome maintained at about
–20

C (Leica Microsystems Ltd, Milton Keynes, UK), and
sagittal sections (nominal thickness, 30 mm) were obtained
through the carcass to include the following tissues: exorbital
lachrymal gland or ovaries (females), intra-orbital lachrymal
gland, Harderian gland, adrenal gland, thyroid, brain and
spinal cord. The sections, mounted on ‘‘Invisible-Tape’’
(Supapak, Shipley, UK), were freeze-dried in a GVD03
bench-top freeze-drier (Girovac Ltd, North Walsham, UK)
and placed in contact with Fuji imaging plates (BAS-MS,
Raytek Scientific Ltd, Sheffield, UK). [
14
C]-Blood standards
of appropriate activity, also sectioned at a nominal thickness
of 30 mm, were placed in contact with all imaging plates. The
radioactivity present in various organs and tissues in whole-
body sections was determined by quantitative whole-body
autoradiography using a Fuji FLA-5000 image analyser
(FujiFilm) and the PC-based image analysis software package
Seescan2 (LabLogic Ltd, Sheffield, UK). Representative
whole-body sections were placed into close contact with
phosphorimaging screens and left for seven days. On each
phosphorscreen, a set of [
14
C]toluene external standards was
also exposed. After the phosphorscreen was scanned, an
image of the radioactivity in the sample was stored digitally.
For quantitative analysis, two background areas were defined
on each stored phosphorscreen image. The response of each
background region was determined using automatic imaging
data analysis software, and the mean background was
calculated. Each standard was analysed and the mean
background subtracted. The concentrations of radioactivity
were expressed as microgram equivalents of selexipag per
gram of sample (mg eq./g).
Metabolic stability in plasma and liver microsomes
[
14
C]Selexipag was incubated at a final concentration of
10 mMat37

C in a total volume of 500 mL containing plasma
(20% v/v) from Sprague–Dawley rat, beagle dog or cyno-
molgus monkey. [
14
C]Selexipag was incubated under the
same conditions in Tris-HCl (100 mM, pH 7.4) containing
liver microsomes from rat, beagle dog or cynomolgus monkey
(final protein concentration, 1 mg/mL). After 20 min, the
reactions were terminated with 500 mL of acetonitrile. Control
samples were incubated in the same way in the absence of
[
14
C]selexipag, and [
14
C]selexipag was added after the
acetonitrile. The mixtures were centrifuged at 16 080 g for
5 min to remove precipitated protein. Samples of the super-
natants (2–3 mL) were spotted on precoated Silica Gel 60 F
254
plates. The fraction percent of MRE-269 on the TLC plates
was determined as described above under plasma sample
preparation. Assays were performed in duplicate. Plasma
protein concentration was measured using the BCA
(bicinchoninic acid) protein assay kit (Pierce Chemical Co.,
Rockford, IL).
Results
Excretion of radioactivity
After a single oral dose of [
14
C]selexipag to rats, the amount
of radioactivity eliminated in the urine and faeces in the
period 0–168 h after administration accounted for 5.8 and
89% of the dose, respectively (Table 1). After a single
intravenous dose of [
14
C]MRE-269 to rats, the radioactivity in
the urine and faeces accounted for 4.9 and 94% of the dose,
respectively. In all groups, the mean total recovery of
radioactivity, including the cage washings up to 168 h, was
in the range of 95–99%. The radioactivity in the expired air
was less than 0.1% after intravenous administration, demon-
strating that the carbon-14 was in a metabolically stable
position of the molecule. Biliary excretion was the major
elimination pathway after intravenous administration of
[
14
C]selexipag, accounting for 92% of the dose (Table 2).
After oral administration, the biliary route was responsible for
the clearance of 72% of the systemically available drug, as
determined from the combined radioactivity in the bile and
urine. Renal excretion was in the range of 3–6% irrespective
of the dosing route. Cumulative excretion was in excess of
95% at the end of the 168-h collection period. The potential
for enterohepatic recirculation of MRE-269 was investigated
after intravenous administration of [
14
C]MRE-269 to bile-
duct-cannulated rats (Table 3). Bile was collected from dosed
(donor) animals for 3 h and re-infused into the duodenum of
bile-duct-cannulated (receiver) animals. Almost 55% of the
radioactivity administered was reabsorbed by the receiver
rats.
After a single oral and intravenous dose of [
14
C]selexipag
to beagle dogs, the amount of radioactivity eliminated in the
urine and faeces over the period 0–192 h accounted for 5.3
and 79% of the dose, respectively, after oral administration

radioactivity was recovered in the faeces after intravenous

14

Pharmacokinetics of total radioactivity, selexipag and
MRE-269 in plasma
Plasma-concentration–time profiles of total radioactivity,
selexipag and MRE-269 after intravenous and oral adminis-
tration of selexipag to rats and oral administration to
cynomolgus monkeys are shown in Figures 2 and 3. The
pharmacokinetic parameters of total radioactivity, selexipag
and MRE-269 for rats and monkeys are summarised in Tables
4 and 5, respectively. In rats, selexipag could not be quantified
in plasma after oral administration, while the metabolite
MRE-269 reached its maximal plasma concentrations at 1 h
post-dose and then declined with a terminal half-life of 4.2 h
(Figure 2A). After intravenous administration of [
14
C]MRE-
269 to rats, the plasma clearance of MRE-269 was low,
accounting for approximately 27% of the hepatic blood flow,
the volume of distribution was high, and the average apparent
terminal half-life was 6.6 h, similar to that observed after oral
administration of [
14
C]selexipag (Figure 2B). The plasma
levels of total radioactivity showed maximal values at 1 h
post-dose and then declined more slowly than did MRE-269.
MRE-269 accounted for 50% of the total radioactivity.
After oral administration of [
14
C]selexipag to cynomolgus
monkeys, plasma levels reached maximal concentrations at,
on average, 1 h post-dose (Figure 3A). The mean terminal
half-life of selexipag was 7.3 h. MRE-269 reached its
maximal concentrations later than did the parent compound
and then declined with an apparent terminal half-life slightly
longer than that calculated for the parent compound. The
plasma levels of radioactivity reached their maximal values at
4 h post-dose and then declined slowly with a correspondingly
long half-life (88.3 h). Selexipag and MRE-269 accounted for
1.7 and 5.4%, respectively, of the total plasma radioactivity in
monkeys, suggesting that circulating metabolites other than
MRE-269 contributed to the elimination half-life. After
intravenous administration of [
14
C]selexipag and [
14
C]MRE-
269 to monkeys (Figure 3A,B), the plasma clearance was 48
and 32%, respectively, of the hepatic blood flow. The volume
of distribution of MRE-269 (>1 L/kg), which was higher
than that of selexipag, suggests good tissue penetration of
MRE-269.

Discussion
The disposition and elimination of selexipag were investi-
gated in rats, dogs and monkeys. After a single intravenous or
oral dose of [
14
C]selexipag to all three species, more than
74% of the radioactivity was excreted in the faeces with a
smaller fraction excreted in the urine, indicating bile as the
major excretion route of selexipag.
Biliary excretion was the major route of excretion for
[
14
C]MRE-269 as well as [
14
C]selexipag. Renal elimination
was a minor excretion pathway for both compounds and did
not exceed 6% in any of the experiments. The amount of the
total radioactivity detected in rat and dog faeces after oral
administration of [
14
C]selexipag to bile-duct-cannulated ani-
mals reached 8.8–29% of the dose, indicating that the
majority of the [
14
C]selexipag dose was absorbed. Similar
amounts of radioactivity were found in the faeces after
intravenous administration of both compounds, indicating
some degree of direct transfer from the blood into the
gastrointestinal lumen. In the enterohepatic recirculation
study, 55% of the administered radioactivity was reabsorbed
by the receiver rats, indicating that MRE-269 and/or its
metabolites can undergo enterohepatic recycling in the rat.
The tissue distribution studies showed that radioactivity was
distributed throughout the tissues after oral administration of
[
14
C]selexipag to male and female nulliparous albino and
pigmented rats. Maximal concentrations occurred at the first
time point (1 h) in the majority of tissues, and by 72 h
the concentrations were below the limit of detection in the
majority of tissues in all rats. Radioactivity levels in melanin-
containing tissues of pigmented animals were similar to the
corresponding tissues in albino rats, suggesting limited binding
of radioactivity to melanin. In all groups, the radioactivity
levels in the brain and spinal cord were lower than in the
plasma, indicating that little or no drug-related material crossed
the blood/brain barrier. The tissue distribution in the pregnant
dam was comparable to that in the other animals. There was
only limited placental transfer of radioactivity, with levels in
the foetal tissues being much lower than in the dam. This
indicates that the placenta acted as a barrier to [
14
C]selexipag-
related material and blocked its transfer into the foetus.
Plasma levels of selexipag and MRE-269 were assayed by
TLC. Total plasma radioactivity was also measured. In rats,
selexipag was hydrolysed so rapidly that its plasma concen-
tration could not be quantified after oral administration at a
dose of 1 mg/kg. In monkeys, the oral bioavailability of
selexipag was low, whereas the oral absorption of selexipag,
assessed as the urinary recovery obtained after oral admin-
istration as a percentage of that obtained after intravenous
administration, was 75%, suggesting that selexipag was well
absorbed through the gastrointestinal tract. Selexipag showed
moderate clearance, a low volume of distribution and an
apparent plasma half-life of approximately 1.8 h after intra-
venous administration. In both rats and monkeys, the terminal
half-life of MRE-269 was longer than that of selexipag. In
both species also, MRE-269 showed low clearance, a
moderate volume of distribution and an apparent plasma
half-life of approximately 6.6–7.5 h after intravenous admin-
istration of MRE-269.
Selexipag was extensively metabolised in rat plasma,
consistent with the results of previous hydrolysis studies with
nonradiolabeled drug (Nakamura et al., 2007). The selective
hydrolysis of selexipag observed in rat plasma is consistent
with the presence of carboxylesterases in rat but not in dog or
monkey plasma (Li et al., 2005). On the basis of our
observations and previous work, therefore, we consider
carboxylesterases to be responsible for the conversion of
selexipag to MRE-269. Hydrolysis of selexipag to MRE-269
was also observed with NADPH-supplemented liver micro-
somes (Nakamura et al., 2007), suggesting that further
experiments would be required to include or exclude
NADPH-dependent metabolism, which may lead to inter-
species differences in the pharmacokinetics of selexipag.
In summary, selexipag was extensively metabolised in rats
primarily by hydrolysis. Faecal excretion was the major route
